  "exemplar_id": "ex_pulmonary_embolism_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "52-year-old woman presenting with 8 days of sharp pleuritic chest pain (worse with deep inspiration, episodes lasting 15-20 minutes) and progressive exertional dyspnea — now short of breath after 100 meters, where she previously ran regularly. She has a persistent dry cough but no fever, hemoptysis, sputum, or wheeze. She reports palpitations with exertion. She is a long-term smoker (currently half pack per day) with no prior cardiopulmonary history. The doctor has characterized the chest and respiratory symptoms but has not yet explored extra-thoracic findings or thromboembolic risk factors.",
  "good_next_question": "Any calf pain?",
  "rationale": "This question is a deliberate probe for deep vein thrombosis as the source of a suspected pulmonary embolism — a screening move a novice clinician working a chest-pain-plus-dyspnea case might omit because the symptoms are anatomically distant from the presenting complaint. The clinical picture (pleuritic pain, progressive exertional dyspnea, dry cough, palpitations, smoker, middle-aged woman) has a broad differential including PE, pneumonia, pneumothorax, malignancy, and cardiac causes. Asking about calf symptoms tests the unifying hypothesis that this is venous thromboembolic disease: if there is unilateral calf pain or swelling, the case becomes textbook PE-with-DVT until proven otherwise, raising the Wells score and triaging the workup toward D-dimer or straight to CT-PA rather than chest imaging for infection. Asking this beats continuing to characterize the chest pain because it probes a different anatomic system that, if positive, reframes the case and short-circuits the differential. A negative answer doesn't exclude PE but lowers the pretest probability and broadens the workup back to pulmonary and cardiac causes.",
  "tags": [
    "chest_pain",
    "dyspnea",
    "middle_aged",
    "vascular",
    "pulmonary",
    "unifying_hypothesis",
    "pulmonary_embolism"
  ],
